Testing<23;1>
------- <24;1>
<EL>
<2;1>
This document contains a mix of short and long physical lines.<3;5>
<EL>
<4;1>
* Row = A physical screen row.<EL>
<5;1>
* Short line = A physical line of text that display less that `COLS` columns fac<6;1>
toring in tabs.<EL>
<7;1>
* Long line = A physical line of text that can wrap onto two or more logical lin<8;1>
es (screen rows) depending on the terminal width given by `COLS` factoring in ta<9;1>
bs. <EL>
<10;1>
* Logical line = portion of a long line that fits on a single screen row.<11;1>
* BOF = Beginning of file.<12;1>
* EOF = End of file just after last character or newline.<13;1>
* BOL = Beginning of line, which can be BOF.<14;1>
* EOL = End of line at a newline or EOF if no terminating newline.<15;1>
* TOP = Top of page.<16;1>
* BOP = Bottom of page.<18;1>
<EL>
<19;1>
### Terminal Dimensions<21;1>
Historical serial CRT terminals were 80 columns by 24 rows.  Later serial termin<22;1>
als were 80x25 to make room for a status line.  X Windows, Windows, and Mac syst<23;1>
ems have terminal emulators (typically `xterm`, `ansi`, or `vt100`) that can be<24;1>
resized on the fly.  Typically the column width is a multiple of eight (8) to a<2;1>
count for `TAB` stops.  The terminal dimensions can be found with `stty -a` or c<3;1>
heck the `TERM` definition (see `/usr/share/misc/terminfo`) or both.<4;1>
<EL>
<5;1>
Curses library supports the environment variables `TERM`, `LINES`, and `COLUMNS`<6;1>
.  It possible to temporarily set `LINES` or `COLUMNS` or both smaller than the<7;1>
terminal window size for easier testing and debugging, eg.<EL>
<8;1>
<EL>
<9;1>
    $ LINES=10 ./ae file<10;1>
